<p>Well technically both of these are the same but with a slight difference. While  “string” is a datatype, whereas “String” represents a class. “string” is an alias for System.String. At execution time both are compiled to the same code. One more difference is the syntax highlighter.</p>

<p>Let us now check a code snippet to understand both of these.</p>

<pre><code>    using System;  
    using System.Collections.Generic;  
    using System.Linq;  
    using System.Text;  
    using System.Threading.Tasks;  
    namespace ConsoleApplication2  
    {  
        class Program  
        {  
            static void Main(string[] args)  
            {  
                string FirstName = ".Net";  
                String Lastname = "Snippets";  
                Console.WriteLine(FirstName + " " + Lastname);  
                Console.ReadLine();  
            }  
        }  
    }  
</code></pre>
